# TypeScript Standards

## Requirements
- Enable strict mode in all tsconfig files
- Use `unknown` instead of `any` — if `any` is unavoidable, add `// eslint-disable-next-line` with justification
- Prefer `type` over `interface` unless declaration merging is needed
- Use discriminated unions for complex state types
- Always use `as const` for literal arrays and objects
- Never use non-null assertion (`!`) — use proper narrowing instead
- Prefer `satisfies` operator over type assertion when validating shapes

## Import Organization
1. Node built-ins (`node:fs`, `node:path`)
2. External packages (`@nestjs/core`, `zod`)
3. Internal packages (`@company/shared`)
4. Relative imports (`./user.service`)
- Blank line between each group

## Error Handling Pattern

<example>
// ✅ Correct: typed errors with Result pattern
type Result<T, E = Error> = { ok: true; value: T } | { ok: false; error: E };

function parseConfig(raw: string): Result<Config, ParseError> {
  try {
    const parsed = JSON.parse(raw);
    const validated = configSchema.parse(parsed);
    return { ok: true, value: validated };
  } catch (e) {
    return { ok: false, error: new ParseError("Invalid config", { cause: e }) };
  }
}
</example>

<example type="invalid">
// ❌ Wrong: untyped catch, any usage
function parseConfig(raw: any) {
  try {
    return JSON.parse(raw);
  } catch (e) {
    console.log(e);
    return null;
  }
}
</example>
